    <td  bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="TOP"><table width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
      <tr align="left">
        <td  bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width="100%" valign="top"><font color="#08599C">
         <b>Author:&nbsp;<a class=doctorLink href="mailto:&#97;&#108;&#101;&#120;&#97;&#110;&#100;&#114;&#97;&#45;&#99;&#97;&#114;&#100;&#111;&#115;&#111;&#64;&#115;&#97;&#112;&#111;&#46;&#112;&#116;?subject=My (humble) opinion about Marat">Alexandra</a> </b><br>
         <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
           <tr>
             <td><font color="#08599C"><b>Date:&nbsp;</b></font></td>
             <td><DIV DIR="ltr"><font color="#08599C"><b>20-10-2005 05:58</b></font></DIV></td>
           </tr>
         </table>
         <br>
      This is what I think about Marat. <br />
Technically he has huge talent; a huge serve and a comprehensive range of strokes on all aspects of the game (both backcourt and net types of games). He has an athletic game but he can also move fast on court thanks to his good footwork, and he can combine power with touch. All of that is enough to make him the best player of the circuit. Is weakest point is in the mind. It’s not that he cannot strategically plan and play a game, or that he cannot read his opponent’s game. He can do all that to perfection. His fragility lays in the fact that his frame of mind balances between overconfidence and lack of confidence. <br />
He knows his game and his talent so he knows he can be better than anyone, but he also knows that he is a person of moods and that’s what makes his insecure. He can be feeling well, but he never knows what’s going to happen when he gets on court. He likes to control every point and every aspect of the game and therefore he puts to much pressure on himself. He might start playing relaxed and loose, believing that sooner or later he will win the match. He risks some strokes (overconfidence) and they don’t come out right, so he starts having doubts. He then tries to “fix it” by being more conservative (lack of confidence) but that doesn’t work and then he gets angry at himself. Sometimes being angry makes him get a grip on himself and things get into the tracks again, sometimes he looses the balance completely. <br />
It’s always easier to train the body than the mind; you can practice you volley, or your serve, and its relatively straightforward to improve those strokes, but how can you train your mind, how can you improve your confidence? That is something that might come with time. Sometimes people get more solid as they get old, with life’s experiences contributing to that. Other times you can benefit from a coach that has good psychological skills. Marat has already said that Peter is a coach that he can talk to and that has given him confidence, so let’s hope that in 2006, without injuries, all the work they have been developing together might start showing of his fruits.<br />
Of course these are just my personal thoughts. Having never met or talked to Marat, I have no way of really knowing how he really feels of thinks. <br />
Love & kisses<br />
Alexandra</font></tt><p>
